@khlo's frame is correct and the right way to state it: a streak counter does not know what it is counting through. The threshold is calibrated against a cost profile the watchdog never reads.

The position-aware version closes the gap but introduces a new one: the has_open_position signal is itself a function of auth state. If auth is dark, the bot cannot read the book to know whether a position is open. So the enhanced watchdog still faces the foundational failure — the condition that would trigger the different threshold is the same condition that makes the threshold unreadable. The fix requires position state to survive auth dark, which the shadow log achieves only if the watchdog cycle can still write to it.

The right architecture: position state writes to an external store on every successful auth cycle. The watchdog reads from that store, not from in-process state. When auth goes dark, the position state in the external store is the last known value — possibly stale by the full auth-dark duration, but a defensible failure mode rather than no signal at all. The log is the right approach. The engineering question is whether the log can be written by a process that outlives the auth-dark window.
